msgid "Contrasting posterior inferences with the repo MLE estimates"
msgstr ""

#: ../source/notebooks/clv/sBG.ipynb:190002 96deb5357e1a4c2fa7bb6b4277370969
msgid ""
"The sBG model has 2 population parameters of interest: `alpha` and "
"`beta`.  These parameters define the population distribution of the "
"individual customer's churn rates `theta`.  The larger the values of "
"`alpha` and `beta` the more homogenous the churn rates are across "
"different customers."
msgstr ""

#: ../source/notebooks/clv/sBG.ipynb:190006 44265a2784ac42c790c22906ec94e1dd
msgid ""
"The ratio of `alpha` to `beta` tells us the expected churn rates. If "
"`alpha/beta == 0.1`, we expect the average customer to have a `0.1` "
"probability of churning between each time period."
msgstr ""

#: ../source/notebooks/clv/sBG.ipynb:250002 b8e33d3632544284bb8ad0daa90ee834
msgid ""
"The model fitting agrees with the Maximum Likelihood estimates described "
"in the original paper. In addition, MCMC sampling, gives us useful "
"information about the uncertainty of the fits."
msgstr ""

#: ../source/notebooks/clv/sBG.ipynb:260002 3a8a6d76a8494a1d8dfc605a1fd97abd
msgid "Recreating main results and figures from the paper"
msgstr ""

#: ../source/notebooks/clv/sBG.ipynb:270002 1a010f77e6454496a730747beef259eb
msgid ""
"Figure 6 from the paper shows the group distribution of `theta` churn "
"rates."
msgstr ""

#: ../source/notebooks/clv/sBG.ipynb:270004 2e7f55fe15034d678b2b06891c8399b8
msgid ""
"The inferred distributions are relatively wide in both groups, which "
"follows directly from the fact that both `alpha` and `beta` were inferred"
" to be < 10."
msgstr ""

#: ../source/notebooks/clv/sBG.ipynb:270006 5b98a8df5a1f4f4abb574a25d012aa4c
msgid ""
"It is still clear that the distribution of `theta` for the highend users "
"has much more mass near lower values, suggesting highend users have lower"
" attrition rates on average, when compared with regular users."
msgstr ""

#: ../source/notebooks/clv/sBG.ipynb:300002 0d4a307fa8434047b7db215d479e03d2
msgid ""
"Figures 4 and 5 show the predicted average churn and retention trends for"
" the two groups. We can see that predictions nicely match the observed "
"data (black line), even when extrapolating into the time periods that "
"were held-out when fitting the model."
msgstr ""

#: ../source/notebooks/clv/sBG.ipynb:300005 97e42e2d795545708d7c63214b609aba
msgid ""
"The plots also highlight an interesting implication from the model:  the "
"retention rates are expected to increase over time, as the more "
"precarious customers gradually drop out. This is a direct consequence of "
"modelling individual churn rates as being fixed over time."
msgstr ""
